text: This song is wildly viewed as Gura having a conversation with her PL fans, explaining why she left. A lot of her PL fans were unhappy with the new direction Gura went when she joined hololive. That Gawr is voiced the same as her PL lends a lot of credence to the idea that Reflect is aimed at them.
author: @Mindpron

text: While what Mindpron says can be a way to view the song. It's also just a very personal tale of Reflecting on your regrets in life the ones that hold you down the ones that cause you to struggle with yourself. Then accepting those regrets and using them to move forward with determination. That you will not forget the past but you will not let it define or hold you back anymore.  It's an emotional tale not everyone experiences in life but those that do connect to the message more.
author: @neotagatg3238

text: @neotagatg3238¬† it is a context that many newer fans could miss, but at the time of the release, the Gura fanbase was pretty fractured and had a lot of infighting.

So this song really speaks to anyone who has a darker past or maybe has done the wrong thing in life. As an Oni, I am just saying... it hasn't been always peaches and cakes. But I am happy to say that I am able to live in society now and be awesome and enjoy my life to the fullest. But you shouldn't forget the past, and this is important for all of us. Trying to shut your past out is a quick way to fall into a trap. Realize what you are. Realize what has happened in life. And get past it. Life isn't over yet. Just live for tomorrow, be in today, and never forget your true self. It could be disastrous if you do.

text: Gura has only done one solo original song.  She has collaborated on other songs, for example Q, which is also an original, in conjunction with Mori Colliope, who's "think" is being an american in japan who raps in Japanese, so there will be Japanese in that.  Gura also enjoys singing both English and Japanese songs.  Check around for a wide variety of English songs she's covered.  Furthermore, while Gura herself doesn't really speak japanese, she does have a huge japanese fanbase.  There is no harm in performing some songs in japanese.  She's also done some Japanese covers such as her cover with Shion for Renai Circulation; a song with huge clout in WEEB circles and frankly there is a lot of crossover fans between anime and vtubers.

text:
I keep coming back to this song (because obviously), and more and more I've been noticing something....is it just me, or are the lyrics out of order?
Judging from the final line, and what Gura's said on the matter elsewhere, the lesson seems to be about dealing with your inner critic, not letting it control you, but that shunning it completely will only ever backfire. You need just the right amount of it to be in best shape.
And so in one verse, Gura says goodbye to the red-eyed critic, leaves her past behind her, and proclaims that she'll live by her own rules, true to herself all the way. But that's too far the wrong direction, dismissing an entire facet of who she is, and she reaps the backlash from this before long. ("So, you think that's all, huh?")
In another verse, instead of straight-up saying goodbye to her other half, she apologizes. She admits to having failed to notice what good that side of her has done amidst the bad. That who she is is a product of all of these facets put together. The past isn't something to escape from, it's a part of you and is why you are who you are today. You bring that with you into a brighter future. Hand in hand. Until the end.
And yet these two verses occur in the opposite order from this interpretation. We go from apologizing and saying "I'm me because of you" to saying "goodbye, I'll remember you", seemingly a downgrade in character development. There doesn't even seem to be a proper setup for the "Just gonna leave like it's nothing?" line that happens after. Is this just me missing something? Did the song get scrambled at some point in development? Or is the lesson not what I think it is?
I suppose it does work from the perspective of DID, where the line can start to blur between alters as healing continues, so in that sense you might be saying "goodbye" to them. But as much as Gawr has become her own character, it's clear watching Gura describe Reflect that this wasn't part of her initial intention with it. (It's fun to interpret it that way, though :D)

Her eyes glow with a brilliant red,
Beginning to sink, down into the void deep beneath the sea~

Why do you cry? (Begin to fall)
I got you everything you craved for and desired the most,
Tell me if I, (Your darkest thoughts)

Not ever telling lies, yet the truth never revealed,
Isn't it easier not to say whats in your heart?
A brand new day, (A time and place)
Somewhere to stay, (For darker days)
Is there a time when our minds ever synchronize?

text:
In the context of the song, I personally think Gawr is not "another personality" but more of a past version of Gura. Something like being pressured to be the ruthless ruler of the sea. Being a blood loving shark is what she's supposed to be but she was never just a shark. She tried to fulfill expectations but they never felt fulfilling for her. So one day, she left atlantis and saw the world beyond the shore and decided "this is where I'm happy." In the end, she realized that even if she wasn't entirely happy with how she lived before, she acknowledges that her past has help her get to where she is. That's how she makes peace with her "red" past. 

Damn. I wanna make a whole story about this. With details and all that.

text:
It's fine to not like a song, but to blame this song's direction on cover alone is not right. This is Gura's project, she produced this with the help of her managers and with the team she gathered based on management's recommendations. From the music direction and theme to the genre and even to the MV has been produced by Gura and others I mentioned. If the song and MV's quality is bad for you then blame Gura. :_GuraHAHA:I am not saying that she did a bad job, in fact I like the song, it is unique. Is it the best Hololive song for me? No. 

If you were expecting an animated MV like Q, take note that Gura has mentioned that the MV has been complete for several months before today's release, she never once hyped it up like Calli by saying she hired a well-known animator to make the MV. It was never advertised to be a high-production quality project. It doesn't help that Gura's network is smaller than Calli's (who's far more experienced in producing music AND music videos.) I think I get where you're coming from though, you want cover to assist Gura from step zero to 100% completion of a project like normal musical artists do. Except for some reason cover only gives them a fixed budget for a song and the talents have full creative freedom to do whatever. I think what Gura or other holos need is a producer. She recently just mentioned she has a whole graveyard of (incomplete to complete) song projects. Gura is also very shy and introverted and If she hires a very hands-on producer I think it might help her make bigger projects while not having to do the networking herself.

text:
Yeah... I always assumed this song, and her general shark persona, was about the idea of being predatory as a human being. I always associate it with internet toxicity, and rather then going with the tide of bullying others based on bandwagoning, thinking for yourself and doing something cringe(like being a goody two shoes hololive streamer). Hearing it reminds me of who I am, and who I was. I always assumed that was to be the original intention of the song, since she too said it was a sort of self-reflection in her post-song interview.
It first realeased at an interesting time for me, when i was starting to become a better person and a kinder version of myself. And from the begginning, gura helped me with that. When the song dropped, i was in a sort of transitory period where i was learning not to be some memer edgelord and hate whatever it was popular to hate at the time(i think it was dream around the time the song dropped lol). It helped me realize that yes, it was time to move on and become a better version of myself, but at the same time, that part of me would never truly leave, and i should accept it as something that formed who I am today. I am the sum total of all that I am, even my worst sides.
That is what this song means to me and thats why its one of my favorites

text:
¬†@PhantomGato-v-¬† i disagree, red Gura is still current Gura

My reading of the song is that Gura struggles because she cannot truly be herself as the Gawr Gura character ("No lies, but no truths either, isn't it easier to never say what you really mean?") and she feels confined, but at the same time her current success is everything she wanted ("I got you everything you craved") and she's scared that she cannot succeed without it ("A shark is all you'll ever be").

Red Gura is the side of her that tells her to just "Accept your fate and chill", to continue riding the wave of success as Gawr Gura.

Don't misunderstand, I don't think Gura hates her job or anything, but this is a recurring theme you will find in a lot of Vtuber songs. Being successful as someone who isn't really you can be kinda depressing, and coming to terms with that is what Reflect is about, I believe.

text:
¬†@BaneHydra¬† First, this is good thought. However, "Return to the sea. A shark is all you'll ever be" may not be so literal. Her lore as being a shark girl in Atlantis is one that finds a new life as a fish out of water. It may or not be reminiscent of a certain rascal cutting loose on the net for comedy, but it is straightly referring to the past. Red tells her she is "a bad, bad shark". It doesn't have to be directly talking about a past persona, but it is talking about a set of traits she sees as negative, or viewed negatively she struggles with. The latter of which Gura more or less confirmed on her song talk video for Reflect as she wasn't truly happy with who she was, but it got her here.

With "accept your fate and chill" I think you're mostly right on. Red Gura is still current Gura, but so is Blue, and not. Someone who pushed the envelope as a rascal now working for an "idol company" was something you could see her struggle with particularly early on as Gura. But while she's got that red rascal, and the blue cute thing she wants to be, she knows those parts are at odds with each other, and that those are just parts she wonders "Will we find common ground?" This is all to say she probably wants to one day be herself, and known wholly rather than some isolated traits conforming to people's interests. Until then, as "One story ends." and she "Begin(s) again" she will remember her Red while appreciating the support she's received as Blue.

We've got a song that repeatedly goes back and forth looking for a person's dominant facets and asking what is false. There really are a lot of ways to read this song. Like how Red asks, "Be yourself? Do you know who you are?" It could be calling her out for someone that will always be a rascal, or it could be saying she doesn't actually know who she is. However she feels about the song, it is a beautiful struggle with oneself, and the desire to keep looking for answers.
author: @ShenSeiken

text:
¬†@ShenSeiken¬† Yeah, they're both current Gura, all great art is an expression of emotion and conflict.

I see the "You're a bad, bad shark" part as red Gura taunting herself over being fake. Basically, we only get to see the happy, shiny parts of the talents, but they have struggles in their lives that they have to hide from us. So there is probably a part of her that fears that if we knew who she "really" was, we wouldn't like her. And those worries are expressed through red Gura nagging at herself.

"Return to the sea, a shark is all you'll ever be", as I mentioned, means that she feels like she is stuck with the persona. Again, her doubts and fears, represented by red Gura, tell her to shut up and return to the sea, to just continue being the cute shark, because in her mind that's all she's good for.

But that's just my interpretation, yours make sense too. It really is a well written song that's clearly very close to her.
author: @BaneHydra

text: ¬†@BaneHydra¬† good analysis. However, as a longer time fan from before her debut as a Vtuber, I only mostly agree. While Red Gura is indeed basically a side of Gura who wants her to relax and chill, but also can be, mind that, can be symbolic of her past

text:
Even trying to analyse the AMV was difficult lmao. Every frame was timed with the beat of the music and changed as fast as you saw it lmao. Almost as difficult to follow as Max0r‚Äôs editing. And that‚Äôs saying something.
Reflect‚Äôs AMV seems to focus more on the lore aspect and how it ties to the character of Gawr Gura while the song itself shows both her and the woman behind the screen. The AMV shows Gura has been reflecting (roll credits) on her time in Atlantis and having thoughts about how her past self would react to her now. She believed her past self would be disdainful of the current Gura, actively provoking her, attacking her insecurities and trying to convince her to return to how she used to be. Just going with the flow. Never reaching out. Stagnating. But the visuals also show bloody waters and even skulls floating down, hinting that past Gura was very violent and luxuriated in her power. The shattered rock floating in the sea might mean that Gura‚Äôs home, Atlantis, was attacked and while Gura successfully saved the city, a lot was still destroyed. This might have shaken past Gura‚Äôs confident view of herself and made her take a look at her actions, whereupon she decided she didn‚Äôt like the person she had become and had to leave and find who she wanted to be. Reflect‚Äôs AMV obviously doesn‚Äôt take part wholly in the past of course. This is present Gura looking back on her past. And up until the end, her past seems to have been weighing down on her. Trying to drag her into the deep, the blood and destruction she once thrived in that she now fears. Until the end where she reaches her resolution. She acknowledges that the person she was has been instrumental in making the person she is now and won‚Äôt simply run away from it. She accepts it and can move on from the past that haunted her for so long. A lot of this can be found in the song on its own obviously. Past Gura, Guralter, Gawr, whatever you call her has the role of an antagonist. She insults Gura‚Äôs intelligence, her pride, her appearance and tries to tear her down. ‚ÄúNow look at this so called ‚Äúgem of the sea‚Äù! Odd and scrawny, see what I mean? Return to what ya know, it ain‚Äôt much I know‚Ä¶it shows‚Äù. These are her insecurities personified in a vicious representation of her past self. Gura starts out trying to plead with them, she‚Äôs scared and hurt by her insecurities. She doesn‚Äôt want to be judged by a ghost of her past for failing to live up to her expectations. She tried so hard to be herself that being torn down the way she was must have been crushing. But it doesn‚Äôt doesn‚Äôt let up: If you don‚Äôt conform why were you even born? Be yourself? Do you even know who you are? All you‚Äôll get doing this is pain. Then we get this ‚ÄúReturn to the sea, a shark is all you‚Äôll ever be‚Äù which can be taken to mean: ‚ÄúGo home and quit the life and happiness you‚Äôve tried to build for yourself. You will never be more than your past mistakes, but at least it will be better than the new pain you‚Äôre inflicting on yourself searching for a new you.‚Äù But Gura eventually realised that‚Ä¶yes. Her past will never go away. However she learned to accept it. That the life she has now is worth it to keep going forward and keep realising her dreams. There is a lot of thought and meaning behind this song and even then I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôve scratched the surface of it with this mini analysis. If anyone else has anything they saw in the lyrics or the AMV itself that they want to add or even contradict my own you‚Äôre free to do so. I‚Äôm interested in hearing other people‚Äôs thoughts on it.
Edit: added some things that I had to look up the lyrics I posted on the original to find because they added quite a bit more depth to the analysis.

text: ¬†@ivansantoso3462¬† no that's wrong, or at least partly wrong. It doesn't refer to people, only that there is no bad thing in life (or in general) that doesn't contain something good in it. That's it, where you choose to apply the saying then is up to you. Sometimes the saying is also reversed, to point out that good things also contain something bad in them, so that people should always be cautious. Be hopeful when something terrible happens, because you can focus and nurture the good that is contained in it, but also be cautious of something that appears to be good (in the inverse statement) because it may also bring terrible consequences

text:
There's at least 1 hour's worth of lore in this trailer.

Gawr is, from what we know, the Gura from long ago in Atlantis. The guilt of her past self's actions weigh on Gura's mind, and she deals with the pain of regret and trying to move forward into her new self. But Gawr is always a part of Gura, and Gura is learning to say goodbye to that past self. 

Gawr is under the sea, and its a metaphor of how Gura feels where Gawr should stay. She has left her, and has risen out the water as Gura.
